# Table 1: Mean and median departure delay per airport
departure_delay <- flights %>%
  left_join(airports, by = c("origin" = "faa")) %>%
  group_by(name) %>%
  summarise(
    mean_dep_delay = mean(dep_delay, na.rm = TRUE),
    median_dep_delay = median(dep_delay, na.rm = TRUE),
    flight_count = n()
  ) %>%
  filter(flight_count >= 10) %>%
  arrange(desc(mean_dep_delay)) %>%
  select(name, mean_dep_delay, median_dep_delay)
print(departure_delay, n = Inf)

# Find the aircraft model with the fastest average speed
fastest_aircraft <- flights %>%
  left_join(planes, by = "tailnum") %>%
  group_by(model) %>%
  summarise(
    avg_speed = mean(speed, na.rm = TRUE),
    num_flights = n()
  ) %>%
  arrange(desc(avg_speed)) %>%
  slice(1)
print(fastest_aircraft)

get_temp <- function(temp_month, temp_year, data, celsius = FALSE, average_fn = mean) {
  # Check if temp_month is numeric and within the valid range
  if (is.numeric(temp_month)) {
    if (temp_month < 1 || temp_month > 12) {
      stop("Invalid month: Please provide a numeric (1-12) or string (e.g., 'Jan') month.")
    }
  }
  
  # Convert month to numeric if it's provided as a string (first three letters)
  temp_month <- ifelse(is.numeric(temp_month), temp_month, substring(temp_month, 1, 3))
  
  # Filter the data for the specified year and month, selecting the temperature column
  t <- data %>%
    filter(year == temp_year, (month_numeric == temp_month | month == temp_month)) %>%
    select(temp)
  
  # Return the average temperature, converting to Celsius if required
  return(ifelse(celsius, (average_fn(t$temp) - 32) * 5 / 9, average_fn(t$temp)))
}

# Plotting sales price over time

  geom_point(alpha = 0.3, color = "lightblue") +

# Transform data to long format for genres
art_sales_genre <- art_sales %>%
  pivot_longer(cols = starts_with("Genre___"),
               names_to = "genre",
               values_to = "value") %>%
  filter(value == 1) %>%  
  mutate(genre = case_when(
    genre == "Genre___Sculpture" ~ "Sculpture",
    genre == "Genre___Photography" ~ "Photography",
    genre == "Genre___Print" ~ "Print",
    genre == "Genre___Painting" ~ "Painting",
    genre == "Genre___Others" ~ "Others",
    TRUE ~ NA_character_  
  )) %>%
  select(-value)
# Plotting genre distribution across years
ggplot(art_sales_genre, aes(x = year, fill = genre)) +
  geom_bar(position = "fill") +  
  scale_y_continuous(labels = percent_format()) +
  labs(title = "Distribution of Genre of Sales Across Years",
       x = "Year",
       y = "Proportion of Sales") +
  scale_fill_brewer(palette = "Pastel2") +
  theme_minimal() +
  theme(text = element_text(size = 10),
        plot.title = element_text(hjust = 0.5, face = "bold"),
        axis.title = element_text(face = "bold"),
        legend.title = element_blank(), 
        legend.position = "bottom")

The data shows that the distribution of photography, print and sculpture increase over time, whereas painting and other arts experience a decline.

# Plotting sales price over time by genre
ggplot(art_sales_genre, aes(x = year, y = price_usd, color = genre)) +

        axis.title = element_text(face = "bold"),
        legend.title = element_blank(), 
        axis.text.x = element_text(angle = 45, hjust = 1),
        legend.position = "right")
`geom_smooth()` using formula = 'y ~ x'

Photography slowly increased over time, reaching its peak in 2007 before gradually declining. Print experienced a decrease starting in 2000, followed by an increase, and then declined again after its peak in 2008. Sculpture, painting, and other genres followed a similar trend, first rising and then falling mildly.
